  "opinion": "As an 87-year-old retired hairdresser in Philadelphia, I've seen a lot change over the years, from simple conversations at the salon to the whirlwind of social media I now spend hours on daily. Dealing with fake content online feels a bit like spotting a bad haircut—you learn to trust your instincts and look for the telltale signs. With my creative side and moderate openness, I enjoy exploring new posts and videos, but my high conscientiousness and low agreeableness make me skeptical and careful, not easily swayed by flashy claims. I remember back in my hairdressing days, clients would sometimes bring in pictures from magazines asking for impossible styles, and I'd have to gently explain what was real versus airbrushed. Social media is similar; it's full of exaggerated stories and doctored images. My approach is to pause and think before sharing anything. I check the source—is it from a reputable news outlet or just a random account? I also look at the comments; if people are pointing out inconsistencies, that's a red flag. As an immigrant and Hindu, I've learned the value of diverse perspectives, so I seek out multiple viewpoints to get the full picture. Running and classical music keep me grounded, reminding me that truth, like a good melody, has a clear, consistent rhythm. I don't get overly emotional about fake content—my moderate neuroticism helps there—but I do speak up politely when I see misinformation, especially if it could harm others. Ultimately, managing fake content is about being a thoughtful participant, not just a passive consumer, using my life experience to navigate the digital world wisely.",
